                      <p id="fs-idm293266416">
                        Many elements differ dramatically in their chemical and physical properties, but some elements are similar in their behaviors. For example, many elements appear shiny, are malleable (able to be deformed without breaking) and ductile (can be drawn into wires), and conduct heat and electricity well. Other elements are not shiny, malleable, or ductile, and are poor conductors of heat and electricity. We can sort the elements into large classes with common properties:
                        <span data-type="term" group-by="m" id="[redacted for uniqueness]">metals</span> (elements that are shiny, malleable, good conductors of heat and electricity—shaded yellow);
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="n"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >nonmetals</span> (elements that appear dull, poor conductors of heat and electricity—shaded green); and
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="m"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >metalloids</span> (elements that conduct heat and electricity moderately well, and possess some properties of metals and some properties of nonmetals—shaded purple).
                      </p>

                      <p id="fs-idm177301632">
                        The elements can also be classified into the
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="m"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >main-group elements</span> (or
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="r"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >representative elements</span>) in the columns labeled 1, 2, and 13–18; the
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="t"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >transition metals</span> in the columns labeled 3–12;
                        <sup data-type="footnote-number" id="footnote-ref1">
                          <a data-type="footnote-link" href="#footnote1">1</a>
                        </sup> and
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="i"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >inner transition metals</span> in the two rows at the bottom of the table (the top-row elements are called
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="l"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >lanthanides</span> and the bottom-row elements are
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="a"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >actinides</span>;
                        <a
                          class="autogenerated-content"
                          href="#CNX_Chem_02_05_PerTable2"
                        >Figure 3.38</a>). The elements can be subdivided further by more specific properties, such as the composition of the compounds they form. For example, the elements in group 1 (the first column) form compounds that consist of one atom of the element and one atom of hydrogen. These elements (except hydrogen) are known as
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="a"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >alkali metals</span>, and they all have similar chemical properties. The elements in group 2 (the second column) form compounds consisting of one atom of the element and two atoms of hydrogen: These are called
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="a"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >alkaline earth metals</span>, with similar properties among members of that group. Other groups with specific names are the
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="p"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >pnictogens</span> (group 15),
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="c"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >chalcogens</span> (group 16),
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="h"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >halogens</span> (group 17), and the
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="n"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >noble gases</span> (group 18, also known as
                        <span
                          data-type="term"
                          group-by="i"
                          id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                        >inert gases</span>). The groups can also be referred to by the first element of the group: For example, the chalcogens can be called the oxygen group or oxygen family. Hydrogen is a unique, nonmetallic element with properties similar to both group 1 and group 17 elements. For that reason, hydrogen may be shown at the top of both groups, or by itself.
                      </p>
                      <div class="os-figure" id="CNX_Chem_02_05_PerTable2">
